SIMPLE: reprimand
RECORDS: 2

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Reprimand
<hw>Rep"ri*mand</hw> <pr>(r?p"r?-m?nd)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[F.
<ets>r⟦eacute⟧primande</ets>, <ets>fr</ets>. L. <ets>reprimendus</ets>,
<ets>reprimenda</ets>, that is to be checked or suppressed, fr.
<ets>reprimere</ets> to check, repress; pref. <ets>re-</ets> re +
<ets>premere</ets> to press. See <er>Press</er>, and cf.
<er>Repress</er>.]</ety> <def>Severe or formal reproof; reprehension,
private or public.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Goldsmith gave his landlady a sharp <qex>reprimand</qex> for her
treatment of him.</q> <rj><qau>Macaulay.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Reprimand</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Reprimand
<hw>Rep"ri*mand</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos>
<conjf>Reprimanded</conjf>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Reprimanding</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[Cf. F.
<ets>r⟦eacute⟧primander</ets>. See <er>Reprimand</er>,
<pos>n.</pos>]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To reprove severely; to reprehend;
to chide for a fault; to consure formally.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Germanicus was severely <qex>reprimanded</qex> by Tiberius for
traveling into Egypt without his permission.</q>
<rj><qau>Arbuthnot.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To reprove publicly and officially, in execution of
a sentence; <as>as, the court ordered him to be
<ex>reprimanded</ex></as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><syn><b>Syn.</b> -- To reprove; reprehend; chide; rebuke; censure;
blame. See <er>Reprove</er>.</syn>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Reprimander</ent>⟦br⟧
